Week 05 Lesson Notes — Lab 02: Certificate Revocation (OCSP / CRL)

1. Core Concept

This lab focused on how systems check if a certificate is still trustworthy after issuance, using:

OCSP (real-time validation)
CRL (pre-published revocation lists)

2. Why It Matters

Certificates can be compromised. Revocation ensures that:

Stolen or misused certificates are invalidated
Systems do not trust compromised identities

Without revocation, trust would be static and insecure.

3. Technical Breakdown

Definition

Revocation is the process of marking a certificate as no longer valid before its expiration date.

Components
Leaf certificate
Issuer certificate
OCSP responder
CRL distribution point
Flow
Client receives certificate
Extracts OCSP/CRL info
Queries responder or checks CRL
Determines status: good / revoked / unknown
Trust Implications
A revoked certificate = immediate loss of trust
Trust depends on external validation systems

4. Common Misconceptions
“If a cert isn’t expired, it’s valid.”
It may be revoked
“OCSP and CRL are interchangeable.”
OCSP = real-time, CRL = static list

5. Where This Shows Up
Web security (browser validation)
Internal enterprise systems (identity verification)
Cloud environments (certificate validation services)
DevOps workflows (secure service communication)
Mental Model

Trust is not permanent — it must be checked continuously.

Week 05 Lesson Notes — Lab 03: Certificate Expiration & Replacement

1. Core Concept

This lab focused on certificate expiration, how expired certificates behave, and how to replace them.

Expiration is a built-in mechanism that enforces periodic renewal of trust.

2. Why It Matters

Expired certificates are one of the most common causes of outages:

Websites stop working

APIs fail

Secure connections break

Organizations must monitor and rotate certificates proactively.

3. Technical Breakdown
Definition

Expiration is the predefined validity window of a certificate (notBefore → notAfter).

Components
Certificate validity period
System clock (critical for validation)
Replacement certificate
Flow
Certificate is issued with validity dates
System checks current time vs expiration
If expired → connection fails
New certificate must be generated and deployed
Trust Implications
Expired certificate = not trusted
Even valid cryptography is rejected if time validity fails

4. Common Misconceptions
“Expired certs still work internally.”
They fail validation everywhere
“You can extend a certificate.”
You must replace it

5. Where This Shows Up
Web security (browser errors)
Internal enterprise systems (service outages)
Cloud environments (load balancers, gateways)
DevOps workflows (certificate rotation pipelines)
Mental Model

Trust has a time limit — if not renewed, it expires.

Final Mental Model Across All Labs

Identity + Trust + Verification

Identity → Certificate proves who you are
Trust → Signed by a trusted authority
Verification → Must pass:
Format compatibility
Revocation checks
Expiration checks

A certificate is only trusted if it continuously passes validation.
